\section{The problem}

\subsection{The Problem}

\miniframeson
\begin{frame}[c]{Clientelism and the Expected Utility Theory}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item The EUT was one of the first theories of decision making under risk.\pause
    \item Since its introduction, it has \emph{dominated} political science as a field (including the vote-buying lit.).\pause
    \item {\bf The problem}: the (whole!) literature assumes that in the party's decision-making process:\pause
              \begin{enumerate}
                  \item {\color{blue}Losses and gains affect in a {\bf comparable} way}.\\
                  {\scriptsize\color{gray}Winning elections {\bf feels good as} losing one hurts.}\pause
                  \item {\color{blue}Parties focus only on {\bf absolute} levels of utilities}.\\
                  {\scriptsize\color{gray}Overlooking {\bf changes} in outcomes respect to a reference point (``sunk costs'').}\pause
              \end{enumerate}
        \item These assumptions have led to several empirical inconsistencies.\pause
          \begin{enumerate}
            \item Clientelist Targeting.
            \item Political Contestation.
          \end{enumerate}
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\subsection{The Problem: Clientelist Targeting}

\miniframeson
\begin{frame}{Not Clear Who Clientelist Parties Target}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Since constituencies are well known to clientelist parties, they allocate resources to {\bf core voters}.\\
    {\tiny\color{gray}Cox and Mccubbins (1986).}\pause
    \item Since allocating resources to individuals who ex-ante vote for the party is a waste, parties target {\bf swing voters}.\\
    {\tiny\color{gray} Dixit and Londregan (1996) and Stokes (2005).}\pause
    \item Some state ``that our knowledge of who parties target remains incomplete.''\\
    {\tiny\color{gray} Carlin and Moseley (2015).}\pause
    \item {\color{blue}We contend that this is a \emph{very} important question, yet one that the literature has \emph{failed} to answer}.
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\subsection{The Problem: Political Contestation}

\miniframeson
\begin{frame}{Not Clear The Role of Political Contestation on Vote Buying}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item The more contested an election, the more risks of losing the election, the more vote buying.\\
    {\tiny\color{gray} Scott (1972), Shefter (1977), Diaz-Cayeros (2008), Corstange (2018).}\pause
    \item However, some find very high levels of vote-buying in {\bf uncontested} elections.\\
    {\tiny\color{gray} Gonzalez-Ocantos, Jonge, et al. (2012).} \pause
    \item {\color{blue}Why would a party buy such a massive amount of votes in a safe and uncontested election?}
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

